25 July 2019

Introduction

  • 22% of the UK population live in poverty (JRF, 2018).

  • 67% of adults living in poverty reside in households where at least one individual is in work (JRF, 2018).

  • The majority of low paid jobs are held by part-time employees (Resolution Foundation, 2019).

  • Part-time employees are frequently primary or sole earners in their household.

  • One in eight part-time workers reports wanting to work more hours (ONS, 2018).

  • Decreasing in-work poverty rates appears to be a case of increasing both pay and hours.

Introduction

  • Most research addresses this problem from angle of low hourly pay, rather than few working hours.
    • Exceptions include Cai et al. (2014)
  • For instance, Cai et al. (2018) look at the transition probabilities from low paid work to high-paid work to assess whether low pay is a stepping stone or a trap.
    • See also Cappellari and Jenkins (2008a, 2008b), Fok et al (2015) and Cai (2014).

  • Here, we look at progression from part-time paid employment to full-time paid employment

  • This also has relevance to the DWP given conditionality requirements in Universal Credit.

Introduction

  • Most work on low pay looks at single transitions, rather than sustained change (e.g., Cai et al., 2018)

  • The Resolution Foundation (2017) adopt a different approach, tracking a cohort of low paid individuals over ten years to see how many “escape” or remain “stuck”.
    • Trajectories grouped using logical rules.
    • For instance, escape defined as high paid in each of final three years.
  • But, the logical rule approach can be arbitrary and infeasible.
    • With 3 states (no-pay/low-pay/high-pay) and 10 time periods, there are 59,049 possible sequences.
    • Why not high paid in each of final two years?

Introduction

  • Here we use Sequence Analysis to categorise labour market trajectories over 36 months after leaving part-time paid employment.

  • Sequence Analysis uses information within the labour market trajectories themselves to group similar trajectories together.

  • With this we can:
    • assess what the typical experiences are after leaving part-time employment
    • explore the characteristics of the individuals having these experiences.
  • In short, we can:
    • distinguish sustained transitions from short-term transitions
    • create more flexible categories for other typical labour market experiences.

Introduction

  • To explore which characteristics are associated with different trajectory types, I combine Sequence Analysis with Multistate Modelling using the SAMM method developed by Studer et al. (2018).

  • Specifically, I take 36 month subsequences initiated by a transition from part-time paid employment to another labour market state.

  • Then, I group similar sequences together using sequence analysis.

  • Finally, I run a set of Cox models with the groups defining the events.
    • i.e.I predict the harzard rate of exiting part-time employment into a particular trajectory type.

Introduction

Introduction

Data

  • British Household Panel Survey (BHPS) and Understanding Society (UKHLS).

  • Data runs from 1991-2018 (26 waves overall).

  • Household panel surveys with individuals interviewed each year.

  • Panel is unbalanced: individual enter and exit at different times.

  • At first interview, participants asked for start date of current job.

  • At succeeding interviews, participants asked for dates of changes in employment status since previous interview.

  • From this, we construct a monthly labour market trajectory from start of initial job to end of follow-up.

Data

  • Individuals can be in one of 6 (self-reported) states:
    • Full-Time Paid Employment
    • Part-Time Paid Employment
    • Full-Time Self Employment
    • Part-Time Self Employment
    • Unemployment
    • Not in the Labour Force (NILF)

  • We subdivide into paid employment and self-employment because the surveys go back to 1991, and in earlier years the gig economy was a smaller phenomenon.

  • There is no historical pay data in the surveys, so we cant split into low-pay/high-pay work.

Data

  • We limit to those with part-time paid employment spells.

  • We exclude spells begun before age 18 to (partly) remove summer jobs or jobs held alongside education.

  • We stop follow-up at age 60 to exclude those of retirement age.
    • Mistake: should be 57.
  • There are four issues with this data:
    • Seam effects
    • Spurious transitions
    • Measurement error
    • Selection bias for initial jobs

Methods: Sequence Analysis

  • Sequence Analysis involves two steps.

  • In the first step, a matrix of “dissimilarties” is created containing a measure of dissimilarity for each pair of sequences in the data.

  • Many algorithms for measuring dissimilarity exist.
    • See Studer and Ritschard (2016) for a review

  • Here we use Optimal Matching (OM).

  • In OM, the distance between two sequences is the number of operations required to convert one sequence into the other.

  • Operations are insertions, deletions, and substitutions of states.

Methods: Sequence Analysis

Methods: Sequence Analysis

  • Operations are also assigned a cost to distinguish between different operations.

  • For instance, a substitution between unemployed and inactive may be assigned a lower cost than unemployed and full-time work as these are more qualitatively similar.

  • There are many ways of setting costs
    • See Studer and Ritschard (2016) for a review.

  • Here we use transition probabilities.

  • A substitution between two states has a higher cost if there are few transitions between the two states observed in the data.

  • Note, different cost functions - and different dissimilarity algorithms - can produce different results from the data (Piccarreta and Studer, In Press).

Methods: Sequence Analysis

  • The second step is to use a clustering algorithm to extract groups of similar sequences from the dissimilarity matrix.

  • Standard cluster analysis algorithms can be used.

  • I use the Partioning Around Medoid (PAM) method.

  • To extract k clusters, PAM first selects k partitioning observations and places remaining observations in a cluster with closest partitioning observation.

  • Partitioning observations then swapped until within cluster variance is minimised.

Methods: Sequence Analysis

  • I carry out sequence analysis for transitions to full-time work and to other states, separately.

  • I run PAM for k from 2 to 20 in each case.

  • I select final k based on visual inspection of index plots and Average Silhouette Width (ASW) measure.

  • ASW captures degree to which observations are similar within clusters and dissimilar across clusters.

  • ASW is bounded between -1 and 1. Kaufman and Rousseeuw (1990) propose following rules:
    • 0.71 - 1.0: Strong structure
    • 0.51 - 0.7: Reasonable structure
    • 0.26 - 0.5: Weak, potentially artifical, structure
    • <= 0.25: No structure.

Methods: Sequence Analysis

  • ASW alone is not sufficient to choose correct numbers of clusters.

  • Qualitative assessment also required to make sure clusters are meaniningful (Piccarreta and Studer, In Press).

Methods: SAMM

  • The result of the Sequence Analysis is a categorical variable which groups similar trajectories together.

  • This variable can be used an any other variable.
    • An independent variable to predict some outcome (e.g.association between trajectory and later mental health).
    • A dependent variable to be predicted by some other variables (e.g differences in trajectories by gender/age).

  • Here, we use the clusters to define events in a multistate model.

  • Specifically, we estimate a set of Cox models where the event is a transition from part-time employment into one of the trajectory types.

Methods: SAMM

  • In a given Cox model, the data are coded as censored if:
    • An individual does not exit part-time employment by end of follow up
    • An individual exits within the final three years
    • An individual exits into a different trajectory type.

  • This is a Competing Risks style set up.

  • Exit from part-time employment into one trajectory type precludes moving into another trajectory type.

Methods: Model Covariates

  • I use the multistate model to predict the hazard of exiting part-time employment into different trajectory types.

  • I add several variables to these models to assess how the hazard rate differs across groups of individuals.

  • In particular, I add information on:
    • Gender
    • Age (grouped)
    • Educational attainment
    • Parent of a child under 16
    • Ethnicity
    • UK-wide unemployment rate
    • Pre/Post introduction of National Minimum Wage.

  • Limited by variables that are fixed or measured monthly.

Methods: Model Covariates

  • To explore differences by gender, I add interactions between sex and age, education and parenthood.

  • As individuals may have multiple spells, I add a random effect (frailty term) for individual.

  • I also add random effect for year.

  • Note, because of data collection procedure, the sample is biased towards long spells and spells that last longer in earlier years.

  • By definition, I only observe spells before first interview if they are continuing.

Methods: Model Covariates

  • To (attempt to) get around this, I add indicator variables for:
    • Whether spell began before first interview
    • Whether current month is before first interview

  • Data is interval coded (left and right censored) with one observation for each month a part-time spell lasts.

  • Note, I cannot just exclude initial jobs because this creates bias in opposite direction.

  • Suggestions welcome.

Methods: Software, etc.

  • Data unweighted due to unbalancedness of panel.

  • Complete case analysis only as standard software doesnt exist to impute missing sequence data for unbalanced panels.

  • Data cleaned in Stata.

  • Analysis carried out in R using TraMineR (Gabadinho et al., 2015) and WeightedCluster (Studer, 2013) packages for sequence analysis and coxme (Therneau, 2019) package for mixed-effects Cox models.

  • Code adapted from that provided by Matthias Studer. Email me for liam.wright.17@ucl.ac.uk.

  • Average 3.17 cases per sequence (8,943 sequences overall)

Results

  • Unemployment rate associated with exits into long-term unemployment and no-time/part-time cycling.
    • But, some measurement error in this variable given seam effects in date changes.
  • Introduction of National Minimum Wage (NMW) associated with exits into sustained full-time work and part-time/full-time cycling, but also long-term unemployment.
    • Recent review of effects of NMW notes little evidence of strong negative effects on hours (Low Pay Commission, 2019).
    • Results consistent with increase in hours for some individuals (possibly due to price effects) but lower employment for others.
    • But, effects may be biased in this direction, so unclear whether this is spurious.
      • Indeed, effects positive for all six groups (though insignificant for some).
  • No consistent associations with ethnicity found.

Summary

  • There is a wide diversity in the labour market experiences people have following part-time employment.

  • Individuals typically move on to at least two other states in the 36 months following exit.

  • Using Sequence Analysis, we group these trajectories into sixteen types.
    • The clusters explain the majority of the variation in the sequence data.
  • Destinations differ across several characteristics.
    • Notably, men more likely to enter long term unemployment, women more likely make sustained exits from labour market (though, self report data!).
    • Evidence men with children more likely to stay in work and move into full time work than women with children.
    • Gradients by education more pronounced for long term unemployment than more temporary labour market exits (particularly for men)

Summary

  • Some of the effect sizes are substantial.

  • Differences across characteristics more pronounced when looking at trajectory, rather than initial transition.
    • Women less likely to exit into sustained full-time employment, but not less likely to cycle.

  • Results show value of sequence analysis approach.

Limitations

  • Sample is biased
    • How to get around this?
  • Measurement issues in the data
    • Date of hours change not collected
    • Inconsistencies
    • Self-report data
  • Heterogeneity within clusters, similarity between.
    • Associations may be driven by atypical individuals (Piccarreta and Studer, In Press).
    • Different dissimilarity and clustering measures could given different results.

  • Few variables included in models.

  • Explored part-time paid employment but self-employment still interesting.
